&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;1.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;ORGANIZATION AND SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Organization&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Monster Beverage Corporation (the &amp;#8220;Company&amp;#8221;
 &amp;#8220;Monster&amp;#8221;
 &amp;#8220;Hansen&amp;#8221; or &amp;#8220;Hansen Beverage Company&amp;#8221;) was incorporated in Delaware on April&amp;#160;25
 1990. The Company is a holding company and has no operating business except through its consolidated subsidiaries.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Nature of Operations&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company develops
 markets
 sells and distributes &amp;#8220;alternative&amp;#8221; beverage category beverages primarily under the following brand names: Monster Energy&amp;#174;
 Java Monster&amp;#174;
 X-Presso Monster&amp;#174;
 Monster Energy Extra Strength Nitrous Technology&amp;#174;
 Monster Rehab&amp;#174;
 Peace Tea&amp;#174;
 Hansen&amp;#8217;s&amp;#174;
 Junior Juice&amp;#174;
 Blue Sky&amp;#174;
 Vidration&amp;#174;
 Worx Energy&amp;#174;
 and Hubert&amp;#8217;s&amp;#174;. The &amp;#8220;alternative&amp;#8221; beverage category combines non-carbonated ready-to-drink iced teas
 lemonades
 juice cocktails
 single-serve juices and fruit beverages
 ready-to-drink dairy and coffee drinks
 energy drinks
 sports drinks
 and single-serve still water (flavored
 unflavored and enhanced) with &amp;#8220;new age&amp;#8221; beverages
 including sodas that are considered natural
 sparkling juices and flavored sparkling beverages.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Basis of Presentation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The accompanying consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America (&amp;#8220;GAAP&amp;#8221;) and include the accounts of the Company and its consolidated subsidiaries.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company consolidates all entities that it controls by ownership of a majority voting interest. All intercompany balances and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company considers all highly liquid investments with an original maturity of three months or less from date of purchase to be cash equivalents. Throughout the year
 the Company has had amounts on deposit at financial institutions that exceed the federally insured limits. The Company has not experienced any loss as a result of these deposits and does not expect to incur any losses in the future.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 40pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Investments&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company&amp;#8217;s investments in debt securities are classified as either held-to-maturity
 available-for-sale or trading
 in accordance with Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &amp;#8220;FASB&amp;#8221;) Accounting Standards Codification (&amp;#8220;ASC&amp;#8221;) 320. Held-to-maturity securities are those securities that the Company has the positive intent and ability to hold until maturity. Trading securities are those securities that the Company intends to sell in the near term. All other securities not included in the held-to-maturity or trading category are classified as available-for-sale. Held-to-maturity securities are recorded at amortized cost which approximates fair market value. Trading securities are carried at fair value with unrealized gains and losses charged to earnings. Available-for-sale securities are carried at fair value with unrealized gains and losses recorded within accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) as a separate component of stockholders&amp;#8217; equity. ASC 820 defines fair value as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. ASC 820 also establishes a fair value hierarchy which requires an entity to maximize the use of observable inputs
 where available (see Note 3). Under ASC 320-10-35
 a security is considered to be other-than-temporarily impaired if the present value of cash flows expected to be collected are less than the security&amp;#8217;s amortized cost basis (the difference being defined as the &amp;#8220;Credit Loss&amp;#8221;) or if the fair value of the security is less than the security&amp;#8217;s amortized cost basis and the investor intends
 or will be required
 to sell the security before recovery of the security&amp;#8217;s amortized cost basis. If an other-than-temporary impairment exists
 the charge to earnings is limited to the amount of Credit Loss if the investor does not intend to sell the security
 and will not be required to sell the security
 before recovery of the security&amp;#8217;s amortized cost basis. Any remaining difference between fair value and amortized cost is recognized in other comprehensive income (loss)
 net of applicable taxes. The Company evaluates whether the decline in fair value of its investments is other-than-temporary at each quarter-end. This evaluation consists of a review by management
 and includes market pricing information and maturity dates for the securities held
 market and economic trends in the industry and information on the issuer&amp;#8217;s financial condition and
 if applicable
 information on the guarantors&amp;#8217; financial condition. Factors considered in determining whether a loss is temporary include the length of time and extent to which the investment&amp;#8217;s fair value has been less than its cost basis
 the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer and guarantors
 including any specific events which may influence the operations of the issuer and our intent and ability to retain the investment for a reasonable period of time sufficient to allow for any anticipated recovery of fair value.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Accounts Receivable &amp;#8211;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;The Company evaluates the collectability of its trade accounts receivable based on a number of factors. In circumstances where the Company becomes aware of a specific customer&amp;#8217;s inability to meet its financial obligations to the Company
 a specific reserve for bad debts is estimated and recorded
 which reduces the recognized receivable to the estimated amount the Company believes will ultimately be collected. In addition to specific customer identification of potential bad debts
 bad debt charges are recorded based on the Company&amp;#8217;s recent loss history and an overall assessment of past due trade accounts receivable outstanding.&amp;#160; In accordance with ASC 210-20-45
 in its consolidated balance sheets
 the Company has presented accounts receivable
 net of promotional allowances
 only for those customers that it allows net settlement. All other accounts receivable and related promotional allowances are shown on a gross basis.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Inventories are valued at the lower of first-in
 first-out
 cost or market value (net realizable value).&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Property and Equipment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Property and equipment are stated at cost.&amp;#160; Depreciation of furniture and fixtures
 office and computer equipment
 computer software
 equipment
 and vehicles is based on their estimated useful lives (three to ten years) and is calculated using the straight-line method. Amortization of leasehold improvements is based on the lesser of their estimated useful lives or the terms of the related leases and is calculated using the straight-line method. Normal repairs and maintenance costs are expensed as incurred. Expenditures that materially increase values or extend useful lives are capitalized. The related costs and accumulated depreciation of disposed assets are eliminated and any resulting gain or loss on disposition is included in net income.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Capitalized Software Costs&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; In accordance with ASC 350-40
 the Company capitalizes certain costs incurred in connection with developing or obtaining internal use software. Costs incurred in the preliminary project stage are expensed. All direct external costs incurred to develop internal use software during the development stage are capitalized and amortized using the straight-line method over the remaining useful lives. Costs such as maintenance and training are expensed as incurred.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Intangibles&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Intangibles are primarily comprised of trademarks representing the Company&amp;#8217;s exclusive ownership of the Monster Energy&amp;#174; trademark in connection with the manufacture
 sale and distribution of supplements and beverages and the Hansen&amp;#8217;s&amp;#174; trademark in connection with the manufacture
 sale and distribution of beverages. The Company also owns a number of other trademarks in the United States as well as in a number of countries around the world.&amp;#160; In addition
 the Company owns the Blue Sky&amp;#174; trademark
 which was acquired in September&amp;#160;2000
 and the Junior Juice&amp;#174; trademark
 which was acquired in May&amp;#160;2001. In accordance with ASC 350
 intangible assets with indefinite lives are not amortized but instead are measured for impairment at least annually
 or when events indicate that an impairment exists. The Company calculates impairment as the excess of the carrying value of its indefinite-lived assets over their estimated fair value. If the carrying value exceeds the estimate of fair value a write-down is recorded. The Company amortizes its trademarks with finite useful lives over their respective useful lives
 which range from 1 to 25 years. For the fiscal years ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 2011 and 2010
 there were no impairments recorded.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Long-Lived Assets&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Management regularly reviews property and equipment and other long-lived assets
 including certain definite-lived intangible assets
 for possible impairment. This review occurs annually
 or more frequently if events or changes in circumstances indicate the carrying amount of the asset may not be recoverable.&amp;#160; If there is indication of impairment
 management then prepares an estimate of future cash flows (undiscounted and without interest charges) expected to result from the use of the asset and its eventual disposition. If these cash flows are less than the carrying amount of the asset
 an impairment loss is recognized to write down the asset to its estimated fair value. The fair value is estimated using the present value of the future cash flows discounted at a rate commensurate with management&amp;#8217;s estimates of the business risks. Preparation of estimated expected future cash flows is inherently subjective and is based on management&amp;#8217;s best estimate of assumptions concerning expected future conditions. For the fiscal years ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 2011 and 2010
 there were no impairment indicators identified. Long-lived assets held for sale are recorded at the lower of their carrying amount or fair value less cost to sell.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Foreign Currency Translation and Transactions&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The accounts of the Company&amp;#8217;s foreign subsidiaries are translated in accordance with ASC 830. Foreign currency transaction gains and losses are recognized in interest and other income
 net
 at the time they occur. Net foreign currency exchange gains or losses resulting from the translation of assets and liabilities of foreign subsidiaries whose functional currency is not the U.S.&amp;#160;dollar are recorded as a part of accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) in stockholders&amp;#8217; equity. Unrealized foreign currency exchange gains and losses on certain intercompany transactions that are of a long-term investment nature (i.e.
 settlement is not planned or anticipated in the foreseeable future) are also recorded in accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) in stockholders&amp;#8217; equity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Revenue Recognition&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company recognizes revenue when persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists
 delivery has occurred
 the sales price is fixed or determinable and collectability is reasonably assured. Generally
 ownership of and title to the Company&amp;#8217;s products passes to customers upon delivery of the products to customers.&amp;#160; Certain of the Company&amp;#8217;s distributors may also perform a separate function as a co-packer on the Company&amp;#8217;s behalf. In such cases
 ownership of and title to the Company&amp;#8217;s products that are co-packed on the Company&amp;#8217;s behalf by those co-packers who are also distributors
 passes to such distributors when the Company is notified by them that they have taken transfer or possession of the relevant portion of the Company&amp;#8217;s finished goods. Net sales have been determined after deduction of promotional and other allowances in accordance with ASC 605-50. Amounts received pursuant to new and/or amended distribution agreements entered into with certain distributors
 relating to the costs associated with terminating the Company&amp;#8217;s prior distributors
 are accounted for as revenue ratably over the anticipated life of the respective distribution agreement
 generally 20 years.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Management believes that adequate provision has been made for cash discounts
 returns and spoilage based on the Company&amp;#8217;s historical experience.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 39pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Cost of Sales&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Cost of sales consists of the costs of raw materials utilized in the manufacture of products
 co-packing fees
 repacking fees
 in-bound freight charges
 as well as certain internal transfer costs
 warehouse expenses incurred prior to the manufacture of the Company&amp;#8217;s finished products and certain quality control costs. Raw materials account for the largest portion of the cost of sales.&amp;#160; Raw materials include cans
 bottles
 other containers
 ingredients and packaging materials.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Operating Expenses&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; Operating expenses include selling expenses such as distribution expenses to transport products to customers and warehousing expenses after manufacture
 as well as expenses for advertising
 sampling and in-store demonstration costs
 costs for merchandise displays
 point-of-sale materials and premium items
 sponsorship expenses
 other marketing expenses and design expenses.&amp;#160; Operating expenses also include such costs as payroll costs
 travel costs
 professional service fees including legal fees
 termination payments made to certain of the Company&amp;#8217;s prior distributors
 depreciation and other general and administrative costs.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Freight-Out Costs&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; For the years ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 2011 and 2010
 freight-out costs amounted to $76.1 million
 $60.5 million and $47.4 million
 respectively
 and have been recorded in operating expenses in the accompanying consolidated statements of income.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Advertising and Promotional Expenses&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company accounts for advertising production costs by expensing such production costs the first time the related advertising takes place. A significant amount of the Company&amp;#8217;s promotional expenses result from payments under endorsement and sponsorship contracts. Accounting for endorsement and sponsorship payments is based upon specific contract provisions. Generally
 endorsement and sponsorship payments are expensed on a straight-line basis over the term of the contract after giving recognition to periodic performance compliance provisions of the contracts. Advertising and promotional expenses
 including but not limited to production costs
 amounted to $165.4 million
 $148.8 million and $104.9 million for the years ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 2011 and 2010
 respectively. Advertising and promotional expenses are included in operating expenses in the accompanying consolidated statements of income.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company utilizes the liability method of accounting for income taxes as set forth in ASC 740. Under the liability method
 deferred taxes are determined based on the temporary differences between the financial statement and tax basis of assets and liabilities using tax rates expected to be in effect during the years in which the basis differences reverse. A valuation allowance is recorded when it is more likely than not that some of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. In determining the need for valuation allowances the Company considers projected future taxable income and the availability of tax planning strategies. If in the future the Company determines that it would not be able to realize its recorded deferred tax assets
 an increase in the valuation allowance would be recorded
 decreasing earnings in the period in which such determination is made.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The Company assesses its income tax positions and records tax benefits for all years subject to examination based upon the Company&amp;#8217;s evaluation of the facts
 circumstances and information available at the reporting date. For those tax positions where there is a greater than 50% likelihood that a tax benefit will be sustained
 the Company has recorded the largest amount of tax benefit that may potentially be realized upon ultimate settlement with a taxing authority that has full knowledge of all relevant information. For those income tax positions where there is less than 50% likelihood that a tax benefit will be sustained
 no tax benefit has been recognized in the financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Stock-Based Compensation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company accounts for stock-based compensation under the provisions of ASC 718.&amp;#160; The Company records compensation expense for employee stock options based on the estimated fair value of the options on the date of grant using the Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing formula. The Company records compensation expense for non-employee stock options based on the estimated fair value of the options as of the earlier of (1)&amp;#160;the date at which a commitment for performance by the non-employee to earn the stock option is reached or (2)&amp;#160;the date at which the non-employee&amp;#8217;s performance is complete
 using the Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing formula. Stock-based compensation cost for restricted stock awards and restricted stock units is measured based on the closing fair market value of the Company&amp;#8217;s common stock at the date of grant. In the event that the Company has the option and intent to settle a restricted stock unit in cash
 the award is classified as a liability and revalued at each balance sheet date. See Note 12.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Net Income Per Common Share&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; In accordance with ASC 260
 net income per common share
 on a basic and diluted basis
 is presented for all periods.&amp;#160; Basic net income per share is computed by dividing net income by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during each period. Diluted net income per share is computed by dividing net income by the weighted average number of common and dilutive common equivalent shares outstanding. The calculation of common equivalent shares assumes the exercise of dilutive stock options
 net of assumed treasury share repurchases at average market prices
 as applicable.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Concentration of Risk &amp;#8211;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Certain of the Company&amp;#8217;s products utilize components (raw materials and/or co-packing services) from a limited number of sources. A disruption in the supply of such components could significantly affect the Company&amp;#8217;s revenues from those products
 as alternative sources of such components may not be available at commercially reasonable rates or within a reasonably short time period. The Company continues to take steps on an ongoing basis to secure the availability of alternative sources for such components and minimize the risk of any disruption in production.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;On October&amp;#160;2
 2010
 The Coca-Cola Company (&amp;#8220;TCCC&amp;#8221;) completed its acquisition of the North American business operations of Coca-Cola Enterprises
&amp;#160;Inc. (&amp;#8220;CCE&amp;#8221;)
 through a merger with a wholly owned subsidiary of TCCC. The surviving wholly owned subsidiary was subsequently renamed Coca-Cola Refreshments USA
&amp;#160;Inc. (&amp;#8220;CCR&amp;#8221;)
 and currently distributes certain of the Company&amp;#8217;s products in those portions of the United States in which CCE previously distributed certain of the Company&amp;#8217;s products. Concurrently with this acquisition
 a new entity
 which retained the name Coca-Cola Enterprises
&amp;#160;Inc. (&amp;#8220;New CCE&amp;#8221;) was formed
 which currently distributes certain of our products in Great Britain
 France
 Belgium
 the Netherlands
 Luxembourg
 Monaco and Sweden (added during the first quarter of 2011).&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;CCR
 a customer of the Direct Store Delivery segment (&amp;#8220;DSD&amp;#8221;) with sales within specific markets in the United States and Canada
 accounted for approximately 28% and 29% of the Company&amp;#8217;s net sales for the years ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012 and 2011
 respectively. CCE (including the Coca-Cola Bottling Company up to September&amp;#160;30
 2010) (CCE replaced by New CCE from October&amp;#160;1
 2010)
 a customer of the DSD segment with sales within specific markets in the United States
 Canada
 the United Kingdom and certain countries in Europe
 accounted for approximately 28% of the Company&amp;#8217;s net sales for the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2010.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Credit Risk&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The Company sells its products nationally and internationally
 primarily to full service beverage distributors
 retail grocery and specialty chains
 wholesalers
 club stores
 drug chains
 mass merchandisers
 convenience chains
 health food distributors and food service customers. The Company performs ongoing credit evaluations of its customers and generally does not require collateral. The Company maintains reserves for estimated credit losses
 and historically
 such losses have been within management&amp;#8217;s expectations.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Fair Value of Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The carrying value of the Company&amp;#8217;s financial instruments
 including cash and cash equivalents
 accounts receivable
 accounts payable and accrued liabilities
 approximate fair value due to the relatively short maturity of the respective instruments.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;&amp;#8211; The preparation of the consolidated financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;#160; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Recent Accounting Pronouncements &amp;#8211;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;In February&amp;#160;2013
 the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update (&amp;#8220;ASU&amp;#8221;) No.&amp;#160;2013-02
 &amp;#8220;Comprehensive Income (Topic 220): Reporting of Amounts Reclassified Out of Accumulated Other Comprehensive Income&amp;#8221;. ASU 2013-02 requires an entity to provide information about the amounts reclassified out of accumulated other comprehensive income by component. In addition
 an entity is required to present
 either on the face of the statement where net income is presented or in the notes
 significant amounts reclassified out of accumulated other comprehensive income by the respective line items of net income but only if the amount reclassified is required under GAAP to be reclassified to net income in its entirety in the same reporting period. For other amounts that are not required under GAAP to be reclassified in their entirety to net income
 an entity is required to cross-reference to other disclosures required under GAAP that provide additional detail about those amounts. The guidance is effective for annual and interim periods beginning after December&amp;#160;15
 2013. The adoption of ASU 2013-02 will not have a material impact on the Company&amp;#8217;s financial position
 results of operations or liquidity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In July&amp;#160;2012
 the FASB issued ASU No.&amp;#160;2012-02
 &amp;#8220;Intangibles-Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Testing Indefinite-Lived Intangible Assets for Impairment.&amp;#8221; ASU 2012-02 permits entities to assess qualitative factors first in determining whether the existence of events and circumstances indicates that it is more likely than not that the indefinite-lived intangible asset is impaired. If
 after assessing the totality of events and circumstances
 an entity concludes that it is not more likely than not that the indefinite-lived intangible asset is impaired
 no further analysis would be required. The guidance is effective for annual and interim impairment tests performed for fiscal years beginning after September&amp;#160;15
 2012
 with early adoption permitted. The adoption of ASU 2012-02 will not have a material impact on the Company&amp;#8217;s financial position
 results of operations or liquidity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In June&amp;#160;2011
 the FASB issued ASU No.&amp;#160;2011-05
 &amp;#8220;Presentation of Comprehensive Income.&amp;#8221; ASU 2011-05 eliminates the option to report other comprehensive income and its components in the statement of changes in stockholders&amp;#8217; equity and requires an entity to present the total of comprehensive income
 the components of net income and the components of other comprehensive income either in a single continuous statement or in two separate but consecutive statements. ASU 2011-05 became effective for the Company on January&amp;#160;1
 2012. The adoption of ASU 2011-05 did not have any impact on the Company&amp;#8217;s financial position
 results of operations or liquidity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In May&amp;#160;2011
 the FASB issued ASU No.&amp;#160;2011-04
 &amp;#8220;Amendments to Achieve Common Fair Value Measurement and Disclosure Requirements in U.S. GAAP and IFRS.&amp;#8221; This pronouncement was issued to provide a consistent definition of fair value and ensure that the fair value measurement and disclosure requirements are similar between U.S. GAAP and International Financial Reporting Standards (&amp;#8220;IFRS&amp;#8221;).&amp;#160; ASU 2011-04 changes certain fair value measurement principles and enhances the disclosure requirements particularly for level 3 fair value measurements. ASU 2011-04 became effective for the Company on January&amp;#160;1
 2012. The adoption of ASU 2011-04 did not have any impact on the Company&amp;#8217;s financial position
 results of operations or liquidity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;2.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;INVESTMENTS&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 10pt; TEXT-INDENT: -10pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 8.5pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;Held-to-Maturity&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 46pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The Company&amp;#8217;s investments at December&amp;#160;31
 2012 and 2011 in U.S. Treasuries
 certificates of deposit
 corporate bonds
 municipal securities
 U.S. government agency securities and/or variable rate demand notes (&amp;#8220;VRDNs&amp;#8221;) carried investment grade credit ratings. VRDNs are floating rate municipal bonds with embedded put options that allow the bondholder to sell the security at par plus accrued interest. All of the put options are secured by a pledged liquidity source. While they are classified as marketable investment securities
 the put option allows the VRDNs to be liquidated at par on a same day
 or more generally on a seven day
 settlement basis.&amp;#160; A portion of the Company&amp;#8217;s investments at December&amp;#160;31
 2012 and 2011 in municipal
 educational or other public body securities with an auction reset feature (&amp;#8220;auction rate securities&amp;#8221;) also carried investment grade credit ratings.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=3&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.64%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;3.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;FAIR VALUE OF CERTAIN FINANCIAL ASSETS AND LIABILITIES&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;ASC 820 provides a framework for measuring fair value and requires expanded disclosures regarding fair value measurements. ASC 820 defines fair value as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. ASC 820 also establishes a fair value hierarchy which requires an entity to maximize the use of observable inputs
 where available. The three levels of inputs required by the standard that the Company uses to measure fair value are summarized below.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=3&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Level&amp;#160;1:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Level&amp;#160;2:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Observable inputs other than Level 1 prices
 such as quoted prices for similar assets or liabilities; quoted prices in markets that are not active; or other inputs that are observable or can be corroborated by observable market data for substantially the full term of the related assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Level&amp;#160;3:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt size=2&gt;Unobservable inputs that are supported by little or no market activity and that are significant to the fair value of the assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;ASC 820 requires the use of observable market inputs (quoted market prices) when measuring fair value and requires a Level 1 quoted price to be used to measure fair value whenever possible.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The following tables present the Company&amp;#8217;s held-to-maturity investments at amortized cost as well as the fair value of the Company&amp;#8217;s financial assets that are recorded at fair value on a recurring basis
 segregated among the appropriate levels within the fair value hierarchy at:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table style=WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=100% border=0&gt;
&lt;tr style=HEIGHT: 0px&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 37.62%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=37%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;December&amp;#160;31
&amp;#160;2012&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 2.48%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=top width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.12%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11.82%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=11% colspan=2&gt;

&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.34%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 10.52%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=10%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;796
848&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 0.82%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=top width=0%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 0.72%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=0%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 13pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=4&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The majority of the Company&amp;#8217;s short-term investments are classified within Level&amp;#160;1 or Level&amp;#160;2 of the fair value hierarchy.&amp;#160; The Company&amp;#8217;s valuation of its Level 1 investments
 which include money market funds
 is based on quoted market prices in active markets for identical securities. The Company&amp;#8217;s valuation of its Level 2 investments
 which include U.S. Treasuries
 certificates of deposit
 corporate bonds
 municipal securities
 U.S. government agency securities and VRDNs
 is based on other observable inputs
 specifically a valuation model which utilizes vendor pricing for similar securities. There were no transfers between Level 1 and Level 2 measurements during the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 and there were no changes in the Company&amp;#8217;s valuation techniques.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The Company&amp;#8217;s Level 3 assets are comprised of auction rate securities and put options. The Company&amp;#8217;s Level 3 valuation utilized a mark-to-model approach which included estimates for interest rates
 timing and amount of cash flows
 credit and liquidity premiums
 as well as expected holding periods for the auction rate securities. These assumptions are typically volatile and subject to change as the underlying data sources and market conditions evolve. A significant change in any single input could have a significant valuation impact; however
 no single input has a more significant impact on valuation than another. There were no changes in the Company&amp;#8217;s valuation techniques of its Level 3 assets during the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The following table presents quantitative information related to the significant unobservable inputs utilized in the Company&amp;#8217;s Level 3 recurring fair value measurements as of December&amp;#160;31
 2012.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.08%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 24%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=top width=24%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10.5pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;1.01%-1.61% (1.20%)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;At December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 the Company held auction rate securities with a face value of $27.8 million (amortized cost basis of $20.7 million). A Level 3 valuation was performed on the Company&amp;#8217;s auction rate securities as of December&amp;#160;31
 2012 resulting in a fair value of $5.8 million for the Company&amp;#8217;s available-for-sale auction rate securities (after a $2.5 million impairment) and $17.4 million for the Company&amp;#8217;s trading auction rate securities (after a $2.1 million impairment)
 which are included in short-term and long-term investments.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In June&amp;#160;2011
 the Company entered into an agreement (the &amp;#8220;2011 ARS Agreement&amp;#8221;)
 related to $24.5 million of par value auction rate securities (the &amp;#8220;2011 ARS Securities&amp;#8221;).&amp;#160; Under the 2011 ARS Agreement
 the Company has the right to sell the 2011 ARS Securities including all accrued but unpaid interest thereon (the &amp;#8220;2011 Put Option&amp;#8221;) as follows: (i)&amp;#160;on or after July&amp;#160;1
 2013
 up to $1.0 million aggregate par value; (ii)&amp;#160;on or after October&amp;#160;1
 2013
 up to an additional $1.0 million aggregate par value; and (iii)&amp;#160;in quarterly installments thereafter based on a formula of the then outstanding 2011 ARS Securities
 as adjusted for normal market redemptions
 with full sale rights available on or after April&amp;#160;1
 2016. The 2011 ARS Securities will continue to accrue interest until redeemed through the 2011 Put Option
 or as determined by the auction process
 or should the auction process fail
 the terms outlined in the prospectus of the respective 2011 ARS Securities. Under the 2011 ARS Agreement
 the Company has the obligation
 should it receive written notification from the put issuer
 to sell the 2011 ARS Securities at par plus all accrued but unpaid interest. During the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 $1.3 million of 2011 ARS Securities were redeemed through normal market channels ($3.7 million of par value 2011 ARS Securities were redeemed at par through normal market channels during the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2011). The 2011 Put Option does not meet the definition of derivative instruments under ASC 815.&amp;#160; Therefore
 the Company elected the fair value option under ASC 825-10 in accounting for the 2011 Put Option. As of December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 the Company recorded $1.9 million as the fair market value of the 2011 Put Option
 included in
 prepaid expenses and other current assets
 and other assets
 in the condensed consolidated balance sheet.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In March&amp;#160;2010
 the Company entered into an agreement (the &amp;#8220;2010 ARS Agreement&amp;#8221;)
 related to $54.2 million of par value auction rate securities (the &amp;#8220;2010 ARS Securities&amp;#8221;).&amp;#160; Under the 2010 ARS Agreement
 the Company had the right
 but not the obligation
 to sell the 2010 ARS Securities including all accrued but unpaid interest thereon (the &amp;#8220;2010 Put Option&amp;#8221;)
 under various terms. During the three-months ended March&amp;#160;31
 2012
 the remaining $15.7 million of par value 2010 ARS Securities were redeemed at par through the exercise of the 2010 Put Option
 which exhausted the Company&amp;#8217;s rights under the 2010 ARS Agreement (as of December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 $38.5 million of par value 2010 ARS Securities had been redeemed at par through the exercise of the 2010 Put Option as well as through normal market channels).&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The Company holds additional auction rate securities that do not have a related put option.&amp;#160; These auction rate securities continue to be classified as available-for-sale securities.&amp;#160; The Company intends to retain such investments until the earlier of the recovery in market value or maturity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The net effect of (i)&amp;#160;the revaluation of the 2011 Put Option as of December&amp;#160;31
 2012; (ii)&amp;#160;the revaluation of the Company&amp;#8217;s trading auction rate securities as of December&amp;#160;31
 2012; (iii)&amp;#160;the redemption at par of certain 2011 ARS Securities; (iv)&amp;#160;the redemption at par of certain 2010 ARS Securities
 including those redeemed at par through the exercise of the 2010 Put Option; and (v)&amp;#160;a recognized gain resulting from the redemption at par of a previously other-than-temporary impaired security; resulted in a gain of $0.8 million
 which is included in other income (expense) for the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012. The net effect of (i)&amp;#160;the acquisition of the 2011 Put Option during the second fiscal quarter of 2011; (ii)&amp;#160;the revaluation of the 2011 Put Option and the 2010 Put Option as of December&amp;#160;31
 2011; (iii)&amp;#160;the transfer from available-for-sale to trading of the 2011 ARS Securities during the second fiscal quarter of 2011; (iv)&amp;#160;the revaluation of the Company&amp;#8217;s trading auction rate securities as of December&amp;#160;31
 2011; (v)&amp;#160;the redemption at par of certain 2011 ARS Securities and 2010 ARS Securities
 including those redeemed at par through the exercise of the 2010 Put Option; and (vi)&amp;#160;a recognized gain resulting from the redemption at par of a previously other-than-temporary impaired security during the first fiscal quarter of 2011
 resulted in a (loss) of ($0.8) million included in other income (expense) for the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2011. The net effect of (i)&amp;#160;the acquisition of the 2010 Put Option during the first fiscal quarter of 2010; (ii)&amp;#160;the revaluation of the 2010 Put Option as of December&amp;#160;31
 2010; (iii)&amp;#160;the transfer from available-for-sale to trading of the 2010 ARS Securities during the first fiscal quarter of 2010; (iv)&amp;#160;the revaluation of the Company&amp;#8217;s trading auction rate securities as of December&amp;#160;31
 2010; (v)&amp;#160;the redemption at par of certain 2010 ARS Securities; (vi)&amp;#160;a recognized gain resulting from the redemption at par of a previously other-than-temporary impaired security during the first fiscal quarter of 2010; and (vii)&amp;#160;an increase in the other-than-temporary impairment of certain auction rate securities
 resulted in a (loss) of ($0.8) million included in other income (expense) for the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2010.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 11pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;All amortizing intangibles have been assigned an estimated finite useful life and such intangibles are amortized on a straight-line basis over the number of years that approximate their respective useful lives ranging from one to 25 years (weighted-average life of 20 years). Total amortization expense recorded was $0.05 million
 $0.05 million and $0.05 million for the years ended December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 2011 and 2010
 respectively. As of December&amp;#160;31
 2012
 future estimated amortization expense related to amortizing intangibles through the year ending December&amp;#160;31
 2017 is approximately $0.05 million per year.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
